The critical temperature (often referred to in Wong as the 'critical range') is where the steel's crystal structure changes, allowing heat treatment to be effective. Hardening, annealing, and normalizing all require heating above this range before cooling in different ways. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
The critical temperature is important because it changes the steel's internal structure—not because the steel melts.

This sequence captures the foundation of steel heat treatment. Wong's processes (hardening, annealing, tempering, and normalizing) all begin by heating above the critical range and differ mainly in how the steel is cooled afterward. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🌟 Big Picture:
Every heat-treatment process you're about to learn is simply a different path taken after reaching the austenitic state.

Wong states that hardening is accomplished by rapidly cooling the heated steel through immersion in cold water or oil. Different steels require different quenching media to achieve the desired cooling rate while minimizing cracking. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

💡 Memory Hook:
Hardening = Water or Oil = Rapid Cooling.

Unlike hardening, tempering does not require reheating above the critical range. Instead, the hardened steel is reheated well below the critical range before soaking and cooling in open air. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
If you accidentally exceed the critical range during tempering, you are essentially beginning a new heat-treatment cycle.

Full annealing heats steel above the critical range before slow furnace cooling. Process annealing is performed below the critical range and is intended mainly to restore workability after cold deformation. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🚨 Board Trap:
Many students confuse annealing with process annealing because both contain the word 'annealing.' Always ask: Was the steel cold worked? If yes, think process annealing.

Full annealing heats steel above the critical range before slow furnace cooling. Process annealing is performed below the critical range and is intended mainly to restore workability after cold deformation. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🚨 Board Trap:
Many students confuse annealing with process annealing because both contain the word 'annealing.' Always ask: Was the steel cold worked? If yes, think process annealing.

Wong specifically identifies improved machinability as the principal purpose of spheroidizing. It allows high-carbon steel to be machined more easily before final heat treatment if required. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
The objective is not to prepare the steel for service—it's to make manufacturing easier.

The hard case provides wear resistance, while the tough core prevents brittle failure when the component is subjected to impact or cyclic loading. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
If the entire part were extremely hard, it could crack under shock loading.

Conventional hardening increases the hardness of the steel throughout the hardened section, whereas case hardening is intended to create a hard outer layer while retaining a relatively tough interior. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

🚨 Board Trap:
Don't confuse 'hardening' with 'case hardening.' The word 'case' refers to the hardened outer case or surface.

Carburizing is intended for low-carbon steels because they possess a tough core but cannot develop a very hard surface on their own. By enriching only the surface with carbon, they can subsequently be hardened effectively. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
If the steel already contains a high carbon content throughout, there is much less reason to add additional carbon only to the surface.

Gas carburizing is similar to pack carburizing except that carbon monoxide gas provides the carbon that diffuses into the steel surface. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
The objective remains the same—only the method of supplying carbon changes.

According to Wong, liquid carburizing produces a high-carbon surface by heating the part in a molten salt bath containing sodium cyanide or barium cyanide. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

🚨 Board Trap:
Students often confuse liquid carburizing with cyaniding because both involve cyanide-containing salts. The board may test this distinction, so always pay attention to the process name and objective.

Wong specifically states that a harder case is obtainable by nitriding than by carburizing. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
If maximum surface hardness is the design objective, nitriding is generally the superior choice.

Although both are case-hardening processes, carburizing enriches the surface with carbon while nitriding enriches it with nitrogen. Both improve wear resistance, but nitriding generally produces a harder surface according to Wong. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
Don't memorize process names—memorize what each process diffuses into the surface.

Like carburizing, cyaniding is generally applied to low-carbon steels. The treatment enriches only the surface while preserving the toughness of the low-carbon core. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
The engineer wants a hard skin without sacrificing the naturally tough core.

Cyaniding is performed by immersing the workpiece in a molten cyanide salt bath. The bath supplies both carbon and nitrogen to the steel surface. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
Don't confuse the process with nitriding. Nitriding uses ammonia gas, whereas cyaniding uses a molten cyanide salt bath.

Cold working increases strength through strain hardening but decreases ductility. Process annealing is specifically intended to restore ductility during manufacturing so additional cold-working operations can continue. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
The clue isn't simply 'soften the steel.' The clue is 'continue cold working.'

Shop annealing is a practical heat treatment used to restore sufficient ductility for repair, straightening, or fabrication in the workshop. Wong specifically describes it as heating the steel (about 900°F–1000°F) and then restricting the cooling rate using ashes or lime. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

🧠 Think Like an Engineer:
The keyword is 'repair shop,' not 'factory.'

Wong specifically states that a harder case is obtainable by nitriding than by carburizing. Therefore, when maximum surface hardness is the design objective, nitriding is generally preferred. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

🚨 Board Trigger Words:
Maximum Surface Hardness • Ammonia • Nitrogen → NITRIDING
